rmalized": false, "mention": "AChE", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9794815182685852, "span": {"begin": 631, "end": 635}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:35701"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ester", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9966561794281006, "span": {"begin": 652, "end": 657}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000109"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ACh", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9552828669548035, "span": {"begin": 661, "end": 664}}, {"id": ["mesh:D012694"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "serine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.8990708589553833, "span": {"begin": 672, "end": 678}}, {"id": ["mesh:D017665"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hydroxyl", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.6807953119277954, "span": {"begin": 679, "end": 687}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000109"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Acetylcholine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.995510458946228, "span": {"begin": 709, "end": 722}}, {"id": ["mesh:D012694"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "serine", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9933934807777405, "span": {"begin": 789, "end": 795}}, {"id": ["mesh:D017665"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hydroxyl", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.8195784687995911, "span": {"begin": 796, "end": 804}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:133341"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "choline", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9985330104827881, "span": {"begin": 841, "end": 848}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:43"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "AChE", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.980949342250824, "span": {"begin": 908, "end": 912}}, {"id": ["mesh:D019342"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "acetic acid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9978358745574951, "span": {"begin": 917, "end": 928}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Molecular", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.4768714904785156, "span": {"begin": 1030, "end": 1039}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:43"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ACHE", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9904956817626953, "span": {"begin": 1060, "end": 1064}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6519"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "EC 3.1.1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9847220778465271, "span": {"begin": 1079, "end": 1087}}], "text": "&quot;Acetylcholinesterase is found primarily in blood, brain, and muscle, and regulates the level of the neurotransmitter ACh&nbsp;[acetylcholine] at cholinergic synapses of muscarinic and nicotinic receptors. Acetylcholinesterase features an anionic site (glutamate residue), and an esteratic site (serine hydroxyl group) (Wilson, 2010; Soreq, 2001). In response to a stimulus, ACh is released into the synaptic cleft and binds to the receptor protein, resulting in changes to the flow of ions across the cell, thereby signaling nerve and muscle activity. The signal is stopped when the amine of ACh binds at the anionic site of AChE, and aligns the ester of ACh to the serine hydroxyl group of the enzyme. Acetylcholine is subsequently hydrolyzed, resulting in a covalent bond with the serine hydroxyl group and the subsequent release of choline, followed by a rapid hydrolysis of the enzyme to form free AChE and acetic acid (Wilson, 2010; Soreq, 2001).&quot; [From Russom et al. 2014. Environ. Toxicol. Chem. 33: 2157-2169]  Molecular target gene symbol: ACHE  KEGG enzyme: EC 3.1.1.7", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:17:34 +0000 2026"}